## Commands & Observations
- Typo caught: `find .-iname` → must be `find . -iname`.
- On default macOS (case-insensitive APFS):
  - Only one file can exist per directory differing by case.
  - `find -name` is case-sensitive; `find -iname` is case-insensitive.
  - I matched `./Alpha.txt` (here) and `./test_arena/backup_zone/alpha.txt` (different folder).
**Lesson:** Code as if the world is case-sensitive; use `-iname` only when you truly want case-insensitive search.


Points: What Happened

|||>>>>>>find . -iname "alpha.txt" matched two files:

./Alpha.txt (in your current directory, capital A).

|||________./test_arena/backup_zone/alpha.txt (inside a subfolder, lowercase a).

So:

Both exist, but not in the same folder.

Case difference is preserved (the filesystem remembers).

Your Mac’s APFS volume is case-insensitive by default, so if you tried touch Alpha.txt and touch alpha.txt in the same directory, only one would survive.

⚔️ Lesson for Ritual_032.md

Different directories can contain files that differ only by case.

Same directory cannot (on your default macOS volume).

find -iname is your case-insensitive finder; find -name is strict.

